---

<BlogLayout
  title="Using Wildcards in Scrabble Solvers"
  description="Learn how blank tiles and wildcards work in Scrabble word finders. Understand the ? notation, how solvers handle 26x branching, scoring differences, Free."
  keywords="wildcards scrabble solver, blank tiles word finder, scrabble blank tile strategy, wildcard notation scrabble, question mark solver, blank tile scoring"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Using Wildcards in Scrabble Solvers",
    "description": "Learn how blank tiles and wildcards work in Scrabble word finders. Understand the ? notation, how solvers handle 26x branching, scoring differences, and strategic tips for wildcard searches.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-14",
    "dateModified": "2026-06-26",
    "author": { "@type": "Person", "name": "Raj Naik", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/about/" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/using-wildcards-in-solvers" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do you enter blank tiles in a Scrabble word finder?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Most Scrabble word finders use the ? (question mark) symbol to represent a blank tile. Enter your regular letters plus ? for each blank you have. For example, if your rack is A, T, R, E, and one blank, you'd type 'ATRE?' into the solver. Some tools also accept * (asterisk) or . (period) as wildcard characters." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do blank tiles score zero points in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes — blank tiles always score 0 points regardless of which letter they represent. A blank used as a Z still scores 0, not 10. This is why solvers show different scores for words found with and without blanks. The strategic value of blanks comes from enabling high-scoring positions and bingos, not from direct point contribution." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why do searches with blank tiles take longer in word finders?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Each blank tile multiplies the search space by 26 because it can represent any letter A-Z. With one blank, the solver runs 26 parallel searches. With two blanks, it's 676 (26×26) combinations. Modern solvers still complete these searches in under a second thanks to efficient tree pruning, but the computational work is measurably greater than rack-only searches." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 pt-4 pb-12">
